value.value: An unforeseen and unplanned event or circumstance frequently causing loss or injury.
An accident taking place aboard, or involving, any type of aircraft.
An accident taking place within a home.
An accident taking place on the site of a commercial enterprise.
An accident occurring while aboard, or involving, an automobile.

An autosomal dominant disorder caused by mutation(s) in the FGFR3 gene, encoding fibroblast growth factor receptor 3. The condition is characterized by inappropriate cartilage growth plate differentiation and deficient endochondral growth, manifest clinically with severe rhizomelic short stature, short limbs, characteristic facies with frontal bossing and midface hypoplasia.

A chronic eruption of fibrous papules that develop and fuse to form a thick sclerotic, hypertrophic band at a site of deep folliculitis, usually along the posterior hairline of the scalp. It is most commonly seen in men of African descent.
Deficiency of a coagulation factor that is not caused by genetic alterations. Causes include vitamin K deficiency, amyloidosis, and severe liver disease.
A genetic disorder characterized by craniosynostosis and fusion of the fingers and toes.
A chronic granulomatous inflammation involving the deep dermis and the subcutaneous tissues. It is caused by Actinomycetes bacteria.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the uterine corpus or the cervix. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include leiomyoma, adenomyoma, and endocervical polyp. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include endometrial carcinoma, carcinosarcoma, and cervical carcinoma.
An infectious process caused by bacteria of the Actinomyces species. It is characterized by the formation of purulent and painful abscesses in the mouth, lungs and gastrointestinal tract.
Actinomycotic infection of the face and hands.
Acute hepatitis resulting from ingestion of alcohol.
Atopic conjunctivitis that is of relatively short duration and that has a rapid onset.
An acute inflammatory process that affects the tissues that surround and support the teeth.

An acute and painful inflammatory process that affects the pharynx.  It is usually caused by viruses and less often bacteria. Signs and symptoms include discomfort on swallowing, low-grade fever, headache, and earache.
Ischemia of the intestine that is rapid in onset.

A rare syndrome characterized by an abnormally dilated pupil, hypoflexia, and diaphoresis. The syndrome is usually caused by a viral or bacterial infection. The abnormally dilated pupil is caused by damage to postganglionic parasympathetic fibers innervating the eye.

label.value: Adjustment Reaction with Brief Depressive Reaction

value.value: Temporary maladaptive depressive signs and symptoms associated with a life event.
Inflammation of the appendages of the uterus.
A neoplasm that affects the uvea.  Uveal melanoma is a representative example.
A genetic disorder characterized by defects in the synthesis of cortisol and/or aldosterone, resulting in hyperplasia of the adrenal cortical cells.
The manifestation of psychotic symptoms, such as hallucinations or delusions, in the presence of a mood disorder.

An anxiety disorder characterized by an intense, irrational fear of venturing out into open places or situations in which help (or escape) might not be available should excessive anxiety or panic symptoms develop.

label.value: Agoraphobia without a History of Panic Disorder

value.value: An anxiety disorder characterized by agoraphobia in the absence of a history of panic attacks; the individual fears incapacitation or humiliation in open, public places or situations due to panic-like symptoms rather than a full-blown panic attack.
A sensation of discomfort associated with air travel that may include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, or sweating.
A orthopoxvirus that causes a milder clinical syndrome than smallpox.

A syndrome which occurs in individuals with a history of alcohol abuse. It is caused by prolonged alcohol-induced neurological damage and malnutrition including vitamin and electrolyte deficiencies. Clinical signs include altered mental status, visual impairment and decreased muscle coordination. The clinical course varies and is, in part, dependent upon the severity of symptoms at presentation. The prognosis is poor and worsens if alcohol abuse continues.
Disturbances in psychophysiological functions and responses as a result of  consumption of a beverage containing ethanol.
A genetic hematologic disorder characterized by partial or complete absence of the alpha globin chains of the heme molecule.

An inflammatory interstitial lung disease caused by hypersensitivity reaction to inhalation or ingestion of antigens.  The antigens are usually related to the patient's occupation.  It can present as an acute illness with flu-like symptoms, subacute with repeated episodes of pneumonia, or chronic with dyspnea and productive cough.  The majority of patients recover following the cessation of the exposure to the antigen that causes the disease.  Chronic exposure may eventually progress to interstitial lung fibrosis.

A benign or malignant neoplasm affecting the vagina. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include squamous papilloma and melanocytic nevus. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include carcinoma, melanoma, and sarcoma.
A congenital malformation characterized by the complete absence of all limbs.
An optical condition in the eye where there is an error of refraction of light rays on the retina.

The loss of access to memories that were previously encoded; this disorder is most commonly preceded by trauma, including physical brain injury, stroke, or seizure, but may also be psychogenic in origin. Memory loss may be temporary or permanent, but the ability to encode new memories or skills is not generally affected.

A neurodegenerative disorder characterized by progressive degeneration of the motor neurons of the central nervous system. It results in weakness and atrophy of the muscles which leads to an inability to initiate and control voluntary movements.
Ancylostomiasis that is caused by infection by Ancylostoma Duodenale.
An autosomal recessive disorder that affects the production of beta polypeptide chains which are necessary for the hemoglobin synthesis. Anemia and failure to thrive are characteristic features.
Anemia resulting from the premature destruction of the peripheral blood red cells. It may be congenital or it may be caused by infections, medications, or malignancies.
Hemolytic anemia, the cause of which is not present at birth.
An acquired anemia caused by destruction of the red blood cells by autoantibodies. Causes include autoimmune disorders, lymphoproliferative disorders, and infections.
A congenital hemolytic anemia caused by defects of the erythrocyte membrane, enzyme deficiencies, or hemoglobinopathies.
A benign focal growth composed of vascular tissue.

Anemia caused by the reduction of hemoglobin in relation to the red cell volume. As a result, the red cells have an area of central pallor which is increased in size. The leading cause is iron deficiency.
Anemia that is characterized by increased red blood cell volume.

Anemia characterized by the presence of unusually large erythroblasts in the bone marrow called megaloblasts. It is usually caused by vitamin B12 or folic acid deficiency. Other causes include toxins and drugs.
A blood disorder characterized by the appearance of sickle-shaped red blood cells and anemia.

label.value: Anemia due to Disorder of Glutathione Metabolism

value.value: Anemia resulting from an abnormality of glutathione deficiency.
Lack of sweating or the ability to sweat when provoked by the appropriate stimulus.
